# Day 3 - Linux User Setup with Non-Interactive Shell

## Task
Create a user named `jim` on App Server 2 with a non-interactive shell.

## Objective
Practice creating a restricted Linux account for service or tool access.

## Commands Used
```bash
ssh tony@stapp02
sudo useradd -s /sbin/nologin jim
grep jim /etc/passwd
```

## What the Commands Do
- `ssh tony@stapp02` connects to App Server 2.
- `sudo` runs the command with administrative privileges.
- `useradd` creates the new user account.
- `-s /sbin/nologin` sets the login shell to a non-interactive shell.
- `grep jim /etc/passwd` verifies the account entry.

## Verification
Confirmed that `jim` was created with `/sbin/nologin` in `/etc/passwd`.

## What I Learned
- How to create a restricted user account in Linux.
- Why service accounts should not always have interactive shells.
- How to verify account settings using `/etc/passwd`.

## Personal Notes
This task helped reinforce the difference between a normal user account and a service-style account. It also showed how shell selection controls whether a user can log in interactively.
